  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Colophon on the Royal Edict Scroll of Kim Bong-hwan, Rector of the National Academy
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gochang, an ancient prefecture, has been called by various names—some knew it as Bokju, others as Andong. Its histories have shifted with the times, never holding to a single form. Yet its mountains and rivers remain majestic, possessing that strategic virtue of which it was said: "Two hundred thousand of Qin could match a million of other lords." The customs of its people are pure and gentle, bearing still the legacy of Silla's ancient ways.

    In those days, when the Yuan's Zhizheng reign had turned to the year of the Red-Headed Rebels, more than a hundred thousand strong poured across our borders, driving straight toward Songdo. The late king, moved by alarm, journeyed south and came to rest at Fukuzhou. Troubled by the vast expense of maintaining the royal progress, fearful lest the common people be shaken by disturbance, he consulted with his ministers and appointed Kim Bong-hwan, the great Rector of the National Academy, as prefect of that region to bring order.

    The master rallied officials and people alike, binding them in common purpose and unified strength. He traveled and inspected with tireless concern, and the longer he labored, the more diligent he became. The king found peace in this, and all—from the attending nobles and defending soldiers down to the humblest servants—gained benefit from his care. When the following year brought the rebels to heel, Fukuzhou was elevated to Andong Protectorate, and Kim was raised to the rank of Zhengshun Grandee, receiving imperial edict and commendation.

    Ah, can one not marvel? Without Master Kim's gift for adapting to circumstances and applying wisdom, the provision for the royal progress could not have been accomplished. And had not the officials and people understood the great principle of honoring their sovereign and cherishing their superiors, how could they have obeyed with such unity—every gesture, every whisper followed as command? Surely they deserved to receive together the praise and honor of the imperial pronouncement.

    The master's grandson, the late Remonstrator Jung-gon, has copied the edict and had it mounted as a scroll, wishing to preserve and reverence it eternally, that it might shine forth to his descendants. Thus does he glorify his sovereign's grace and illuminate the virtue of his ancestors. Finding me unworthy of such trust, he sought these words for this colophon. Therefore I write plainly as you see.
  footnotes:
    - The "two hundred thousand of Qin" refers to a historical maxim about the strategic superiority of defended territory over mere numbers.
    - The Red-Headed Rebels (홍두적) were a major insurgent force during the Yuan Dynasty's decline in the mid-14th century.
    - Songdo (松都) is the historical name for Goryeo's capital, modern-day Kaesong.
    - The royal edict scroll being commemorated was itself an honor bestowed upon Kim Bong-hwan for his service during this crisis.
